s"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HOX&nbsp;gene", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8945961594581604, "span": {"begin": 1766, "end": 1779}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3206", "3205", "3198", "3207", "3209", "3202", "3201", "3204", "3200", "3203"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HOX&", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8385201692581177, "span": {"begin": 1766, "end": 1770}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hematopoietic stem cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9122626185417175, "span": {"begin": 1794, "end": 1818}}, {"id": ["mim:601308"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8864482045173645, "span": {"begin": 1853, "end": 1856}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HOX&", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8232709169387817, "span": {"begin": 1863, "end": 1867}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3206", "3205", "3198", "3207", "3209", "3202", "3201", "3204", "3200", "3203"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HOX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9893391728401184, "span": {"begin": 1863, "end": 1866}}, {"id": ["mim:601308"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.99819415807724, "span": {"begin": 2007, "end": 2010}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4297"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MLL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9348418712615967, "span": {"begin": 2032, "end": 2035}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4297"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9729878306388855, "span": {"begin": 2117, "end": 2128}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "promoter regions", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.410837322473526, "span": {"begin": 2256, "end": 2272}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54145"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9962062835693359, "span": {"begin": 2324, "end": 2331}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fusion genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6115739941596985, "span": {"begin": 2402, "end": 2414}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4297"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9817525148391724, "span": {"begin": 2477, "end": 2488}}, {"id": ["CL:0000034"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "stem cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6531344056129456, "span": {"begin": 2587, "end": 2596}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4297"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL product", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918897151947021, "span": {"begin": 2687, "end": 2698}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4298"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL fusion", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.955930233001709, "span": {"begin": 2790, "end": 2800}}, {"id": ["mim:601308"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MLL", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.976947546005249, "span": {"begin": 2920, "end": 2923}}], "text": "Chromosomal rearrangements of the mixed-lineage leukaemia (MLL) gene, located on the q23 band of chromosome 11 (11q23), are the genetic hallmark of most infant leukaemias (Meyer et al 2013; Sanjuan-Pla et al 2015). MLL is located within the fragile site FRA11G; chromosomal fragile sites are regions of the genome susceptible to breakage under conditions of replication stress; interference with TopoII may promote fragile site instability. MLL encodes a protein homologous to the Drosophila trithorax gene, which has relevant functions in embryogenesis and hematopoiesis (Ernest et al 2004, Hess et al 1997).  MLL, a human homologue of the epigenetic transcriptional regulator Trithorax of&nbsp;Drosophila,&nbsp;is an upstream transcriptional effector of&nbsp;HOX&nbsp;genes.&nbsp;The importance of normal MLL protein for normal axial-skeletal developmental process and&nbsp;HOX&nbsp;gene regulation has been demonstrated in the embryos of heterozygous and homozygous&nbsp;MLL&nbsp;knockout&nbsp;and&nbsp;ML mutant mice.&nbsp;Furthermore, expression of MLL protein is not necessary for turning on transcription of certain&nbsp;HOX&nbsp;genes, but for the maintenance of their transcription. Experiments&nbsp;in vitro&nbsp;using hematopoietic progenitors from embryos of homozygous&nbsp;MLL&nbsp;knockout mice&nbsp;or mice with&nbsp;MLL&nbsp;mutant showed that MLL was also critical for hematopoietic development. Recent findings suggested that MLL is required during embryogenesis for the specification or expansion of hematopoietic stem cells. &nbsp;As&nbsp;HOX&nbsp;genes also play a key role in the regulation of hematopoietic development,&nbsp;the hematopoietic dysfunction of&nbsp;MLL&nbsp;null cells is likely to be attributed to deregulated patterns of&nbsp;HOX&nbsp;gene expression in hematopoietic stem cells or progenitors. This link between MLL,&nbsp;HOX&nbsp;gene regulation, and hematopoiesis is of particular importance (Li et al. 2005).  There are many translocation and fusion partners for MLL; DNA breakage within MLL can lead to rearrangement with over 120 partner genes (Meyer et al 2013).&nbsp;  MLL protein (complexed with a large number of other protein factors) serves as a transcriptional activator or repressor via the binding to promoter regions of active genes, marking these regions by covalent histone modifications (Sanjuan-Pla et al 2015). Translocation and creation of fusion genes and products destroys the intrinsic control mechanisms of the MLL protein. The resulting &lsquo;ectopic&rsquo; functions involve promoter hyper-activation and re-acquiring stem cell features (Sanjuan-Pla et al 2015). A schematic presentation of the drastic changes of the MLL product is depicted in the figure below.  &nbsp;    Proposed model for the oncogenic conversion of MLL fusion: A. Physiological situation and B: . A chromosomal translocation, which leads to the intrinsic regulatory mechanism of MLL being destroyed. (Sanjuan-Pla et al. 2015).  &nbsp;  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:41:27 +0000 2026"}